---
import RuntimeLayout from "../../components/RuntimeLayout.astro";
---

<RuntimeLayout
  slug="redelivery"
  description="Why a re-delivered CRDT delta is absorbed as a non-event in watershed: the merge is idempotent by construction, so a duplicate changes nothing after the first — the at-least-once safety an order-based counter cannot offer."
>
  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>At-least-once is the honest assumption</h2>
    <p>
      Real networks do not deliver exactly once. An ack gets lost and the client
      resends; a <a href="/runtime/reconnect">reconnecting</a> peer replays a
      window it already saw; a retry races the original. Sooner or later the same
      update arrives twice. Whether that is harmless or catastrophic depends
      entirely on how the structure absorbs it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Store a running total as a plain last-write-wins integer and a redelivery
      is only the beginning of the trouble — concurrent increments already lose
      each other, as the <a href="/counter-bug">counter bug</a> shows. But even a
      naive operation-based counter that applied deltas directly would break the
      moment one delta arrived twice: "add 5" replayed is <code>+10</code>. The
      total silently drifts, and no sequence number can un-count it.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Merge, don't apply</h2>
    <p>
      watershed's counters are <a href="/models">CRDTs</a>, and a CRDT is built
      so its merge is <strong>idempotent</strong>: merging the same value a
      second time changes nothing. A
      <a href="/structures/counters#pn">PN counter</a> does not ship "add 5"; it
      ships its two grow-only tallies — total fill and total cut — and the
      receiver merges by taking the pairwise maximum of what it has and what
      arrived. Take the max of a number with itself and you get the same number.
      The duplicate lands, the merge runs, and the state does not move.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because correctness lives in the merge and not in the delivery, these
      structures still ride watershed's one sequenced stream but do not
      <em>depend</em> on it for safety. Duplicate delivery is absorbed by the
      data type itself — the guarantee an order-based DDS, which leans on the
      sequence number to dedupe, cannot make for free.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Watch it absorb, live</h2>
    <p>
      The demo makes this witnessable. In PN-counter mode a
      <strong>Re-deliver last delta</strong> button asks the sequencer to re-send
      the last sequenced delta with <em>no new sequence number</em> — a genuine
      duplicate, not a fresh op. The merge swallows it, the signed total holds,
      and the op log records the redelivery as an italic, muted non-event rather
      than a change:
    </p>
    <figure class="oplog" aria-label="Op-log excerpt: a duplicate delta absorbed">
      <div class="oplog-line">
        <span class="oplog-sn">#03</span>
        <span class="oplog-op">cut −5 yd³ → net −5</span>
      </div>
      <div class="oplog-line oplog-dupe">
        <span class="oplog-sn">#03</span>
        <span class="oplog-op">again · cut −5 yd³ · absorbed</span>
      </div>
    </figure>
    <div class="g-note">
      <p>
        <strong>This is the line an op-based counter could not survive.</strong>
        The same delta, delivered twice, has to be a no-op the second time — and
        here it visibly is. It is the sharpest demonstration of why the merge
        model, not the sequence number, is what makes these structures safe under
        an unreliable link.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g-out">
    <span class="annot">In short</span>
    <p>
      CRDT deltas are merged, not applied, and the merge is idempotent — so a
      re-delivered delta is absorbed as a non-event, giving watershed's counters,
      sets, and maps at-least-once safety no order-based structure gets for free.
    </p>
  </div>
</RuntimeLayout>

<style>
  /* op-log excerpt — mirrors the demo's printed log: mono lines, the duplicate
     rendered as a muted italic non-event exactly as the live demo prints it. */
  .oplog {
    margin: var(--space-lg) 0 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--ink);
    background: var(--bg);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
  }

  .oplog-line {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-md);
    padding: 0.5rem var(--space-lg);
  }

  .oplog-line + .oplog-line {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline-faint);
  }

  .oplog-sn {
    color: var(--muted);
    min-width: 3ch;
  }

  .oplog-op {
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .oplog-dupe .oplog-sn,
  .oplog-dupe .oplog-op {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
</style>
